\fs36 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\sa140\ql\qnatural
\cf0 These versatile nuts go beautifully with fresh or aged goat cheese, blue cheese or gruyere.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\ql\qnatural

\f0\b\fs44 \cf0 Ingredients\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sl400\ql\qnatural
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs42 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}1/4 cup powdered sugar\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/8 teaspoon cayenne pepper\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/8 teaspoon salt\
{\listtext	\'95	}4 ounces walnuts (about one heaping cup; don't use pieces)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\ql\qnatural

\f0\b\fs44 \cf0 Directions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\sa140\ql\qnatural

\f1\b0\fs42 \cf0 Preheat the oven to 350 degrees F.\
In a medium sized bowl, mix together the sugar, cayenne and salt.\
Bring a small saucepan of water to boil. Add the walnuts and blanch them for 3 minutes. Drain well and then immediately roll the walnuts in the sugar mixture until thoroughly coated. The sugar will melt slightly. Transfer the walnuts to a baking sheet or pan and bake, stirring occasionally, until they are a deep golden brown, about 10 minutes. Watch carefully because the sugar can burn easily. Let cool completely before serving.}